  "narration": [
    {
      "text": "Photosynthesis is the process plants use to convert sunlight into chemical energy — glucose.",
      "start": 0.5,
      "dur": 7
    },
    {
      "text": "The master equation: six CO₂ plus six water molecules plus light yields glucose and oxygen.",
      "start": 7.5,
      "dur": 7
    },
    {
      "text": "Inside the chloroplast, chlorophyll molecules absorb red and blue light — reflecting green.",
      "start": 16.5,
      "dur": 7.5
    },
    {
      "text": "The absorbed light energy splits water molecules, releasing oxygen and producing ATP — the cell's energy currency.",
      "start": 24.5,
      "dur": 7
    },
    {
      "text": "Carbon dioxide enters through tiny pores called stomata. Water travels up from the roots through the xylem.",
      "start": 33.5,
      "dur": 8
    },
    {
      "text": "Six CO₂ molecules are needed for each glucose made. The split water provides the hydrogen atoms.",
      "start": 42,
      "dur": 7
    },
    {
      "text": "In the Calvin Cycle, ATP energy fixes CO₂ into G3P — the three-carbon building block of glucose.",
      "start": 50.5,
      "dur": 8.5
    },
    {
      "text": "Two G3P molecules combine to form one glucose. The cycle spins continuously in the stroma.",
      "start": 59,
      "dur": 6.5
    },
    {
      "text": "Photosynthesis produces two vital outputs: glucose for energy storage, and oxygen for us to breathe.",
      "start": 67.5,
      "dur": 8
    },
    {
      "text": "Every bite of food traces back to a plant. Without photosynthesis, no oxygen, no food — no life.",
      "start": 76,
      "dur": 7.5
    }
  ]
}

